    {
      "id": "e462da3dd461c2bca6b56ee4823ac98af1819607",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-04-11 12:24:59.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(34 inline comments)\n\nA quick pass through the code.  Lots of style issues.  I didn't look at any of the specific algorithms.\n\nI'd really prefer that the integrity code just be a new checksum type (excluding where the actual T10 data is stored, instead of duplicating all of that code.  If the checksum code is not generic enough to handle this, it should be updated instead of having even more code to duplicate the functionality.\n\nOne idea I had was to store a checksum-of-the-checksums could be stored in the existing o_cksum field to ensure the T10 integrity data itself is valid.\n\nIt would also be good to have at least some comment block at the top of one of the files to describe the integrity data itself and how the protocol works.  Presumably each OST can only have a single T10 sector size?  Is it possible to have different T10 sector sizes for different OSTs?  What happens to the page data in that case?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ee2cb5d563d4555b7f430e3fffb67560ee9dcb17",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 142
      },
      "date": "2013-04-11 13:29:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThank you for the review.\n\nThis patch does not cover checksumming itself, instead it uses the kernel implementation of crc_t10dif(). There is a separate patch (T10-CRC) uploaded to WC gerrit by Alexander Boyko which replaces crc_t10dif() with a faster implementation.\n\nThis patch deals with packing/unpacking/attaching data to page cache pages/attaching data to bios. The code is split between different layers, because it heavily depends on structures from these layers (brw pills/bulks, page cache storage in vvp and osd) even more than ost_checksum_* / osc_checksum_bulk, which themselves do not belong to the checksumming code.\n\nIt is possible to have different chunk sizes for different OSTs, because each page cache page belongs only to one OST and is processed on per-OSC basis. OST MDRAID on top of devices with different chunk sizes will not report itself as DIX-capable.\n\nI will update the patch to include the comments you requested and to fix the style issues.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
